{"title_page": "Wladimir van Wilgenburg", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Journalist and Author}}\n{{Infobox journalist\n| name               = Wladimir van Wilgenburg\n| education          = [[Conflict studies]] and Kurdish studies\n| alma_mater         = [[Utrecht University]]\n| occupation         = Journalist, author\n| notable_works      = ''The Kurds of Northern Syria''\n}}\n\n'''Wladimir van Wilgenburg''' is a Dutch journalist and author writing predominantly about [[Kurdistan]]. He lives in [[Erbil]], [[Iraqi Kurdistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/author/wladimir-van-wilgenburg|title=Bloomsbury - Wladimir van Wilgenburg - Wladimir van Wilgenburg|last=Bloomsbury.com|website=www.bloomsbury.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nVan Wilgenburg received a [[Master of Arts]] in [[conflict studies]] from the [[Utrecht University|University in Utrecht]] in 2011 and another one in Kurdish studies from [[Exeter University RFC|Exeter University]] in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/reporterprofile/4c9e18ad-95b6-4e94-afb7-2391e167a7cf|title=Wladimir van Wilgenburg|last=|first=|date=|website=www.kurdistan24.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for [[Al-Monitor]], [[Kurdistan 24]], [[Al Jazeera|Al-Jazeera]], and [[Foreign Policy]], amongst others.<ref name=\":0\" /> He is also a researcher for the [[Jamestown Foundation]] and his articles are published by the [[Atlantic Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/menasource/the-kurdish-dilemma-counterterrorism-and-realpolitik-in-iraq/|title=The Kurdish Dilemma: Counterterrorism and Realpolitik in Iraq|date=2014-05-16|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHe co-authored the book ''The Kurds of Northern Syria'', together with Harriet Allsop, which was published by [[I.B. Tauris]] in August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/the-kurds-of-northern-syria-9781788315982/|title=The Kurds of Northern Syria|last=Bloomsbury.com|website=Bloomsbury Publishing|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Dutch journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Journalist and Author}}\n{{Infobox journalist\n| name               = Wladimir van Wilgenburg\n| education          = [[Conflict studies]] and Kurdish studies\n| alma_mater         = [[Utrecht University]]\n| occupation         = Journalist, author\n| notable_works      = ''The Kurds of Northern Syria''\n}}\n\n'''Wladimir van Wilgenburg''' is a Dutch journalist and author writing predominantly about [[Kurdistan]]. He lives in [[Erbil]], [[Iraqi Kurdistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/author/wladimir-van-wilgenburg|title=Bloomsbury - Wladimir van Wilgenburg - Wladimir van Wilgenburg|last=Bloomsbury.com|website=www.bloomsbury.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nVan Wilgenburg received a [[Master of Arts]] in [[conflict studies]] from the [[Utrecht University|University in Utrecht]] in 2011 and another one in Kurdish studies from [[Exeter University RFC|Exeter University]] in 2013.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kurdistan24.net/en/reporterprofile/4c9e18ad-95b6-4e94-afb7-2391e167a7cf|title=Wladimir van Wilgenburg|last=|first=|date=|website=www.kurdistan24.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for [[Al-Monitor]], [[Kurdistan 24]], [[Al Jazeera|Al-Jazeera]], and [[Foreign Policy]], amongst others.<ref name=\":0\" /> He is also a researcher for the [[Jamestown Foundation]] and his articles are published by the [[Atlantic Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlanticcouncil.org/blogs/menasource/the-kurdish-dilemma-counterterrorism-and-realpolitik-in-iraq/|title=The Kurdish Dilemma: Counterterrorism and Realpolitik in Iraq|date=2014-05-16|website=Atlantic Council|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nHe co-authored the book ''The Kurds of Northern Syria'', together with Harriet Allsop, which was published by [[I.B. Tauris]] in August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/the-kurds-of-northern-syria-9781788315982/|title=The Kurds of Northern Syria|last=Bloomsbury.com|website=Bloomsbury Publishing|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Dutch journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wladimir_van_Wilgenburg"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Gambino", "text_new": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name             = Thomas Gambino\n| birth_name       = Thomas Francis Gambino\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1929|8|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| nationality      = American\n| parents          = [[Carlo Gambino]]\n| relatives        = [[Paul Castellano]] (uncle)<br>[[Joseph Lucchese]] (uncle-in-law)<br>[[Tommy Lucchese]] (father-in-law)\n| occupation       = [[Mobster]]\n| other_names      = Tommy\n| allegiance       = [[Gambino crime family]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|Frances Lucchese|1962}}\n| conviction       = [[Racketeering]], [[conspiracy]] (1993)\n| criminal_penalty = 5 years' imprisonment\n}}\n'''Thomas Francis Gambino''' ({{IPA-it|\u0261am\u02c8bi\u02d0no|lang}}; born August 23, 1929) is an [[Italian-American]] [[New York City]] mobster and a longtime [[caporegime]] of the [[Gambino crime family]] who successfully controlled lucrative trucking rackets in the New York City [[Garment District, Manhattan|Garment District]]. He is the son of [[Carlo Gambino]] and nephew of [[Paul Castellano]].\n\n==Early life==\nGambino was born on August 23, 1929, to Carlo and Kathryn (n\u00e9e Castellano) Gambino. He had four brothers, Joseph, Carl and Phyllis Gambino Sinatra.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/04/archives/gambino-termed-too-ill-to-quit-u-s.html|title=Gambino Termed Too Ill to Quit U. S.|last=Markham|first=James M.|date=November 4, 1981|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> His father joined the original [[Mangano crime family]] during the 1930s, rose to capo and later to [[underboss]]. In 1957, Carlo Gambino became boss of what is now called the Gambino crime family. Carlo Gambino became one of the most powerful mobsters in [[Cosa Nostra]] history. \n\nThomas Gambino graduated from [[Manhattan College]] in the [[Bronx]] and then started working for the Gambino family. In 1962, Gambino, married [[Tommy Lucchese]]'s daughter Frances.<ref>[http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/3.html The Gambino Crime Family \u2014 A Squirrel of a Man \u2014 Crime Library on truTV.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520091550/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/3.html |date=2013-05-20 }}</ref> Over 1,000 guests attended the wedding, at which Carlo Gambino presented Lucchese with a $30,000 gift. In return, Lucchese gave Gambino a part of his rackets at Idlewild Airport (now called [[John F. Kennedy Airport]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/20/nyregion/police-say-their-chinatown-sting-ties-mob-to-the-garment-industry.html?scp=18&sq=Joseph%20Lucchese%20dies&st=cse | work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|title=Police Say Their Chinatown Sting Ties Mob to the Garment Industry|date=March 20, 1990|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> Lucchese exercised control over airport management security and all the airport unions. As a team, Lucchese and Gambino now controlled the airport, the Commission, and most organized crime in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/05/nyregion/gambino-gained-mob-tax-with-fear-prosecutor-says.html?scp=3&sq=Tommy%20Lucchese%20brother&st=cse |work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Sullivan|first=Ronald|title=Gambino Gained 'Mob Tax' With Fear, Prosecutor Says|date=February 5, 1992|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/1999/05/06/1999-05-06_jailed_capo_out_2m_stuck_in_.html|location=New York|title=Jailed Capo Out 2m Stuck In Stock Scam, Gambino Charges|work=New York Daily News|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608110032/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/1999/05/06/1999-05-06_jailed_capo_out_2m_stuck_in_.html |archivedate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> When Tommy Lucchese died in 1967, his interests in the garment industry were passed to Thomas Gambino, forming the basis of Gambino's wealth.<ref>[http://www.americanmafia.com/Cities/New_York.html \"New York\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212122211/http://americanmafia.com/Cities/New_York.html |date=2010-12-12 }} American Mafia.com</ref>\n\nBy the 1990s, Thomas Gambino owned three homes; one in [[Florida]], another in [[Lido Beach, New York]], and a third on Manhattan's exclusive [[Upper East Side]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/04/nyregion/a-gambino-goes-to-jail-in-1993-case.html?scp=38&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=A Gambino Goes to Jail In 1993 Case|last=Fried|first=Joseph P.|work=New York Times|date=January 4, 1996}}</ref> Thomas Gambino also headed the Gambino Medical and Science Foundation, which in 1991 financed a $2 million [[pediatric]] [[bone marrow transplant]] unit at [[Long Island Jewish Medical Center]]. Thomas Gambino's personal wealth was estimated to be around $75 million in 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/03/nyregion/bare-fisted-violence-or-subtle-threats.html?scp=10&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|title=Bare-Fisted Violence or Subtle Threats?|last1=Gottlieb|first1=Martin|last2=Baquet|first2=Dean|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 3, 1992}}</ref>\n\n==Castellano regime==\nAfter Carlo Gambino died in 1976, his designated successor, [[Paul Castellano]], became the new family boss. Many family members were angered by Castellano's ascension, preferring underboss [[Aniello Dellacroce|Aniello \"Mr. Neil\" Dellacroce]] instead. However, Dellacroce insisted that his supporters support Castellano for the good of the family. This move temporarily quieted the dissension in the Gambino ranks.  \n\nIn contrast, Thomas Gambino, who was Castellano's nephew, enjoyed a strong relationship with the new boss. Gambino epitomized the low-profile, well buffered, successful businessman image common among second generation members of the [[Cosa Nostra]]. Given his college education, Castellano gave him responsibility for the family finances and running the trucking at the [[Garment District, Manhattan|Garment District]] in Manhattan. Gambino and his allies in the Lucchese family were successful at infiltrating several legitimate businesses, especially the garment industry. This was due to Gambino's strong influence on the garment trucking business in New York and New Jersey.<ref>[http://www.mafianj.com/sci89/gambinogottinjops.shtml \"The Gambino/Gotti Family New Jersey Operations\"] State of New Jersey Commission of Investigation 1989 Report</ref> In 1981, the garment industry honored Gambino as its Man of the Year.<ref name=\"garment\">[http://www.apparelsearch.com/Definitions/Miscellaneous/Garment_District_Definition.htm \"Garment District\"] Apparel Search</ref> Castellano quickly rewarded Gambino by making him a full family member, or \"made man\" and later a [[caporegime|capo]] of his own crew.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/05/nyregion/gambino-gained-mob-tax-with-fear-prosecutor-says.html?scp=3&sq=Tommy%20Lucchese%20brother&st=cse|title=Gambino Gained 'Mob Tax' With Fear, Prosecutor Says|last=Sullivan|first=Ronald|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 5, 1992}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/02/nyregion/thomas-gambino-it-s-all-in-the-name.html?pagewanted=1|title=Thomas Gambino: It's All in the Name|last=Barron|first=James|date=December 2, 1992|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=December 9, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"jailed capo\">{{cite news|last=Arena|first=Salvatore|title=JAILED CAPO OUT 2M STUCK IN STOCK SCAM, GAMBINO CHARGES|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/jailed-capo-2m-stuck-stock-scam-gambino-charges-article-1.824488|accessdate=12 April 2012|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=May 6, 1999}}</ref> \n\nIn December 1985, the death of underboss Dellacroce brought the simmering dissension in the Gambino family to a head. Instead of selecting an established and respected capo to be the new underboss, Castellano instead chose his driver, [[Thomas Bilotti]]. At this point, capo [[John Gotti]] and [[Frank DeCicco]] saw the opportunity to capitalize on this discontent to kill Castellano and take over the family leadership. On December 16, 1985, both Castellano and Bilotti were murdered by Gotti gunmen in a restaurant ambush. Gambino, who was not part of the conspiracy, arrived at the restaurant moments after the killing, to be turned away by DeCicco.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shot by Shot, an Ex-Aide to Gotti Describes the Killing of Castellano|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/04/nyregion/shot-by-shot-an-ex-aide-to-gotti-describes-the-killing-of-castellano.html?scp=32&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|work=New York Times|date=March 4, 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304233320/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/04/nyregion/shot-by-shot-an-ex-aide-to-gotti-describes-the-killing-of-castellano.html?scp=32&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> Gotti was then elected the new boss of the Gambino family.\n\n==Gotti regime==\nAlthough Gambino had been a Castellano loyalist, he quickly paid loyalty to Gotti and was able to preserve his position within the family. Since Gambino was such a strong earner for the family, Gotti did not want to replace him. In a conversation with Gambino mobster [[George Remini]], Gotti had this comment about Gambino:\n\n<blockquote>'I mean it sounds crazy, Georgie, but I was telling Frankie and Angelo, I'm gonna suggest to Tommy, we're gonna beef up his regime, Tommy Gambino, but we're not giving him no (expletive deleted) hotheads.'' </blockquote>\n\nIn April 1989, Gambino was indicted for [[obstruction of justice]] by lying to a [[grand jury]] about Gambino racketeering activities, but was acquitted later that year. On October 18, 1990, Gambino was indicted again on charges of extorting the garment industry. Through their ownership of four trucking companies, the Gambinos were able to charge shipping rates 40% higher than smaller non-mob shipping companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/19/nyregion/7-held-in-mob-extortion-of-clothiers.html?scp=27&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|title=7 Held in Mob Extortion of Clothiers|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 19, 1990}}</ref> Some of the strongest evidence in this case came from [[wiretap]]ped conversations six years earlier between Gambino and Castellano at Castellano's [[Staten Island]] home. The conversations proved that the Gambinos and two other crime families exercised strong control over the Garment District.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/30/nyregion/wiretap-evidence-in-gambino-case-links-garment-group-to-mob.html?scp=60&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=Wiretap Evidence in Gambino Case Links Garment Group to Mob|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|date=April 30, 1989|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The government also set up a small garment factory in the Chinatown section of Manhattan, with [[New York State Police]] officers posing as supervisors, to gain evidence against Gambino's trucking monopoly.<ref name=\"gotham\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q6_YXR-DmRgC&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&source=bl&ots=yieWT_D5Pd&sig=b3snUOuM21enElMdhJQafVl-LuA&hl=en&ei=1AXRS8XMN4qQ8gTbrsWpDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CCAQ6AEwCDjSAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&f=false|title=Gotham Unbound: How New York City Was Liberated from the Grip of Organized Crime|last1=Jacobs|first1=James B.|last2=Friel|first2=Coleen|last3=Raddick|first3=Robert|publisher=NYU Press|year=2001|isbn=0814742475|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe government offered Gambino a [[plea bargain]] that included a guilty admission, a $12 million [[restitution]] payment, and a promise to leave the garment trucking business. In February 1992, Gambino accepted the plea bargain and avoided prison.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/16/magazine/the-attorney-general-goes-to-war.html?scp=18&sq=&pagewanted=3 \"The Attorney General Goes To War\"] New York Times Magazine June 16, 2002</ref> Prosecutors would remark that a \"terrifying fear of prison\" helped motivate Gambino to accept the government deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/27/nyregion/gambinos-to-quit-trucking-business-in-a-plea-bargain.html?scp=28&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|title=GAMBINOS TO QUIT TRUCKING BUSINESS IN A PLEA BARGAIN|last=Blumenthal|first=Ralph|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 27, 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304132318/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/27/nyregion/gambinos-to-quit-trucking-business-in-a-plea-bargain.html?scp=28&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Indictment and prison==\nIn 1991, Gambino, Gotti, [[Sammy Gravano|Salvatore \"Sammy the Bull\" Gravano]] and other Gambino mobsters were indicted on charges of racketeering, loansharking, extortion, illegal gambling and 11 counts of murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/12/nyregion/gotti-and-3-top-aides-arrested-on-federal-racketeering-charges.html?scp=23&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=Gotti and 3 Top Aides Arrested On Federal Racketeering Charges|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 12, 1990}}</ref> Soon after the indictment, Gravano decided to become a government witness and testified against his former colleagues, including Gambino.\n\nOn May 11, 1993, Gambino was convicted of two counts of racketeering and racketeering conspiracy. Prosecutors claimed that Gambino had been supervising illegal gambling and [[loansharking]] activities in [[Connecticut]] since 1985.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/12/nyregion/thomas-gambino-is-guilty-of-racketeering.html?scp=2&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=Thomas Gambino Is Guilty of Racketeering|last=|first=|date=May 12, 1993|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=December 9, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 1996, Gambino started serving a five-year prison sentence.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nIn May 1999, the U.S. [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) filed fraud charges against Gambino's stockbroker, Mohammed Ali Khan. While still in prison, Gambino had sued Khan for defrauding him out of approximately $2 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/18/nyregion/metro-news-briefs-new-york-sec-sues-broker-accused-of-theft.html?scp=22&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=METRO NEWS BRIEFS: NEW YORK; S.E.C. Sues Broker Accused of Theft|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 18, 1999}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2000, Gambino was released from prison.<ref>[http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=Thomas&Middle=&LastName=Gambino&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=28&y=20 Bureau of Prisons Inmate Locator]</ref> He has moved to Florida and is now believed to be retired.\n\n==Popular culture==\nThomas Gambino is portrayed by [[Tony Sirico]] in the 1998 made-for-television movie ''[[Witness to the Mob]]'' about Gravano and John Gotti.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Bonanno|first=Joseph|title=A Man of Honor: The Autobiography of Joseph Bonanno|location=New York|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2003|isbn=0-312-97923-1|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Capeci|first1=Jerry|last2=Mustain|first2=Gene|title=Gotti: Rise and Fall|location=New York|publisher=Onyx|year=1996|isbn=0-451-40681-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/gottirisefall00cape}}\n*{{cite book|last=Capeci|first=Jerry|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to the Mafia|location=Indianapolis|publisher=Alpha Books|date=2002|isbn=0-02-864225-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/completeidiotsgu0000cape}}\n*{{cite book|last=Davis|first=John H.|title=Mafia Dynasty: The Rise and Fall of the Gambino Crime Family|location=New York|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993|isbn=0-06-109184-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mafiadynastyrise00davi}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Jacobs|first1=James B.|last2=Panarella|first2=Christopher|last3=Worthington|first3=Jay|title=Busting the Mob: The United States Vs. Cosa Nostra|location=New York|publisher=NYU Press|year=1994|isbn=0-8147-4230-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Maas|first=Peter|title=Underboss: Sammy the Bull Gravano's Story of Life in the Mafia|location=New York|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|year=1997|isbn=0-06-093096-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|title=Five Families: The Rise, Decline, and Resurgence of America's Most Powerful Mafia Empires|location=New York|publisher=St. Martin Press|year=2005|isbn=0-312-30094-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126051608/http://www.thelaborers.net/lexisnexis/articles/verdict_is_termed_a_blow_to_the.htm|last=Blumenthal|first=Ralph|date=November 20, 1986|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=January 24, 2007|url-status=live|title=Verdict Is Termed a Blow to The Mafia}}\n*[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb4298/is_198911/ai_n14997496 Thomas Gambino] on FindArticels\n\n{{Gambino crime family}}{{American Mafia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gambino, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Gambino crime family]]\n[[Category:Manhattan College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Lido Beach, New York]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox criminal\n| name             = Thomas Gambino\n| birth_name       = Thomas Francis Gambino\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1929|8|23}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], U.S.\n| nationality      = American\n| parents          = [[Carlo Gambino]]\n| relatives        = [[Paul Castellano]] (uncle)<br>[[Joseph Lucchese]] (uncle-in-law)<br>[[Tommy Lucchese]] (father-in-law)\n| occupation       = [[Mobster]]\n| other_names      = Tommy\n| allegiance       = [[Gambino crime family]]\n| spouse           = {{marriage|Frances Lucchese|1962}}\n| conviction       = [[Racketeering]], [[conspiracy]] (1993)\n| criminal_penalty = 5 years' imprisonment\n}}\n'''Thomas Francis Gambino''' ({{IPA-it|\u0261am\u02c8bi\u02d0no|lang}}; born August 23, 1929) is an [[Italian-American]] [[New York City]] mobster and a longtime [[caporegime]] of the [[Gambino crime family]] who successfully controlled lucrative trucking rackets in the New York City [[Garment District, Manhattan|Garment District]]. He is the son of [[Carlo Gambino]] and nephew of [[Paul Castellano]].\n\n==Early life==\nGambino was born on August 23, 1929, to Carlo and Kathryn (n\u00e9e Castellano) Gambino. He had four brothers, Joseph, Carl and Phyllis Gambino Sinatra<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/11/04/archives/gambino-termed-too-ill-to-quit-u-s.html|title=Gambino Termed Too Ill to Quit U. S.|last=Markham|first=James M.|date=November 4, 1981|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>. His father joined the original [[Mangano crime family]] during the 1930s, rose to capo and later to [[underboss]]. In 1957, Carlo Gambino became boss of what is now called the Gambino crime family. Carlo Gambino became one of the most powerful mobsters in [[Cosa Nostra]] history. \n\nThomas Gambino graduated from [[Manhattan College]] in the [[Bronx]] and then started working for the Gambino family. In 1962, Gambino, married [[Tommy Lucchese]]'s daughter Frances.<ref>[http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/3.html The Gambino Crime Family \u2014 A Squirrel of a Man \u2014 Crime Library on truTV.com<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520091550/http://www.trutv.com/library/crime/gangsters_outlaws/family_epics/gambino/3.html |date=2013-05-20 }}</ref> Over 1,000 guests attended the wedding, at which Carlo Gambino presented Lucchese with a $30,000 gift. In return, Lucchese gave Gambino a part of his rackets at Idlewild Airport (now called [[John F. Kennedy Airport]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/20/nyregion/police-say-their-chinatown-sting-ties-mob-to-the-garment-industry.html?scp=18&sq=Joseph%20Lucchese%20dies&st=cse | work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|title=Police Say Their Chinatown Sting Ties Mob to the Garment Industry|date=March 20, 1990|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> Lucchese exercised control over airport management security and all the airport unions. As a team, Lucchese and Gambino now controlled the airport, the Commission, and most organized crime in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/05/nyregion/gambino-gained-mob-tax-with-fear-prosecutor-says.html?scp=3&sq=Tommy%20Lucchese%20brother&st=cse |work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Sullivan|first=Ronald|title=Gambino Gained 'Mob Tax' With Fear, Prosecutor Says|date=February 5, 1992|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/1999/05/06/1999-05-06_jailed_capo_out_2m_stuck_in_.html|location=New York|title=Jailed Capo Out 2m Stuck In Stock Scam, Gambino Charges|work=New York Daily News|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608110032/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/1999/05/06/1999-05-06_jailed_capo_out_2m_stuck_in_.html |archivedate=June 8, 2009}}</ref> When Tommy Lucchese died in 1967, his interests in the garment industry were passed to Thomas Gambino, forming the basis of Gambino's wealth.<ref>[http://www.americanmafia.com/Cities/New_York.html \"New York\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101212122211/http://americanmafia.com/Cities/New_York.html |date=2010-12-12 }} American Mafia.com</ref>\n\nBy the 1990s, Thomas Gambino owned three homes; one in [[Florida]], another in [[Lido Beach, New York]], and a third on Manhattan's exclusive [[Upper East Side]].<ref name=\"nytimes.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/01/04/nyregion/a-gambino-goes-to-jail-in-1993-case.html?scp=38&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=A Gambino Goes to Jail In 1993 Case|last=Fried|first=Joseph P.|work=New York Times|date=January 4, 1996}}</ref> Thomas Gambino also headed the Gambino Medical and Science Foundation, which in 1991 financed a $2 million [[pediatric]] [[bone marrow transplant]] unit at [[Long Island Jewish Medical Center]]. Thomas Gambino's personal wealth was estimated to be around $75 million in 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/03/nyregion/bare-fisted-violence-or-subtle-threats.html?scp=10&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|title=Bare-Fisted Violence or Subtle Threats?|last1=Gottlieb|first1=Martin|last2=Baquet|first2=Dean|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 3, 1992}}</ref>\n\n==Castellano regime==\nAfter Carlo Gambino died in 1976, his designated successor, [[Paul Castellano]], became the new family boss. Many family members were angered by Castellano's ascension, preferring underboss [[Aniello Dellacroce|Aniello \"Mr. Neil\" Dellacroce]] instead. However, Dellacroce insisted that his supporters support Castellano for the good of the family. This move temporarily quieted the dissension in the Gambino ranks.  \n\nIn contrast, Thomas Gambino, who was Castellano's nephew, enjoyed a strong relationship with the new boss. Gambino epitomized the low-profile, well buffered, successful businessman image common among second generation members of the [[Cosa Nostra]]. Given his college education, Castellano gave him responsibility for the family finances and running the trucking at the [[Garment District, Manhattan|Garment District]] in Manhattan. Gambino and his allies in the Lucchese family were successful at infiltrating several legitimate businesses, especially the garment industry. This was due to Gambino's strong influence on the garment trucking business in New York and New Jersey.<ref>[http://www.mafianj.com/sci89/gambinogottinjops.shtml \"The Gambino/Gotti Family New Jersey Operations\"] State of New Jersey Commission of Investigation 1989 Report</ref> In 1981, the garment industry honored Gambino as its Man of the Year.<ref name=\"garment\">[http://www.apparelsearch.com/Definitions/Miscellaneous/Garment_District_Definition.htm \"Garment District\"] Apparel Search</ref> Castellano quickly rewarded Gambino by making him a full family member, or \"made man\" and later a [[caporegime|capo]] of his own crew.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/05/nyregion/gambino-gained-mob-tax-with-fear-prosecutor-says.html?scp=3&sq=Tommy%20Lucchese%20brother&st=cse|title=Gambino Gained 'Mob Tax' With Fear, Prosecutor Says|last=Sullivan|first=Ronald|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 5, 1992}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/12/02/nyregion/thomas-gambino-it-s-all-in-the-name.html?pagewanted=1|title=Thomas Gambino: It's All in the Name|last=Barron|first=James|date=December 2, 1992|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=December 9, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"jailed capo\">{{cite news|last=Arena|first=Salvatore|title=JAILED CAPO OUT 2M STUCK IN STOCK SCAM, GAMBINO CHARGES|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/jailed-capo-2m-stuck-stock-scam-gambino-charges-article-1.824488|accessdate=12 April 2012|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=May 6, 1999}}</ref> \n\nIn December 1985, the death of underboss Dellacroce brought the simmering dissension in the Gambino family to a head. Instead of selecting an established and respected capo to be the new underboss, Castellano instead chose his driver, [[Thomas Bilotti]]. At this point, capo [[John Gotti]] and [[Frank DeCicco]] saw the opportunity to capitalize on this discontent to kill Castellano and take over the family leadership. On December 16, 1985, both Castellano and Bilotti were murdered by Gotti gunmen in a restaurant ambush. Gambino, who was not part of the conspiracy, arrived at the restaurant moments after the killing, to be turned away by DeCicco.<ref>{{cite news|title=Shot by Shot, an Ex-Aide to Gotti Describes the Killing of Castellano|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/04/nyregion/shot-by-shot-an-ex-aide-to-gotti-describes-the-killing-of-castellano.html?scp=32&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|last=Lubasch|first=Arnold H.|work=New York Times|date=March 4, 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304233320/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/03/04/nyregion/shot-by-shot-an-ex-aide-to-gotti-describes-the-killing-of-castellano.html?scp=32&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> Gotti was then elected the new boss of the Gambino family.\n\n==Gotti regime==\nAlthough Gambino had been a Castellano loyalist, he quickly paid loyalty to Gotti and was able to preserve his position within the family. Since Gambino was such a strong earner for the family, Gotti did not want to replace him. In a conversation with Gambino mobster [[George Remini]], Gotti had this comment about Gambino:\n\n<blockquote>'I mean it sounds crazy, Georgie, but I was telling Frankie and Angelo, I'm gonna suggest to Tommy, we're gonna beef up his regime, Tommy Gambino, but we're not giving him no (expletive deleted) hotheads.'' </blockquote>\n\nIn April 1989, Gambino was indicted for [[obstruction of justice]] by lying to a [[grand jury]] about Gambino racketeering activities, but was acquitted later that year. On October 18, 1990, Gambino was indicted again on charges of extorting the garment industry. Through their ownership of four trucking companies, the Gambinos were able to charge shipping rates 40% higher than smaller non-mob shipping companies.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/10/19/nyregion/7-held-in-mob-extortion-of-clothiers.html?scp=27&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|title=7 Held in Mob Extortion of Clothiers|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 19, 1990}}</ref> Some of the strongest evidence in this case came from [[wiretap]]ped conversations six years earlier between Gambino and Castellano at Castellano's [[Staten Island]] home. The conversations proved that the Gambinos and two other crime families exercised strong control over the Garment District.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/30/nyregion/wiretap-evidence-in-gambino-case-links-garment-group-to-mob.html?scp=60&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=Wiretap Evidence in Gambino Case Links Garment Group to Mob|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|date=April 30, 1989|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The government also set up a small garment factory in the Chinatown section of Manhattan, with [[New York State Police]] officers posing as supervisors, to gain evidence against Gambino's trucking monopoly.<ref name=\"gotham\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q6_YXR-DmRgC&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&source=bl&ots=yieWT_D5Pd&sig=b3snUOuM21enElMdhJQafVl-LuA&hl=en&ei=1AXRS8XMN4qQ8gTbrsWpDw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CCAQ6AEwCDjSAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&f=false|title=Gotham Unbound: How New York City Was Liberated from the Grip of Organized Crime|last1=Jacobs|first1=James B.|last2=Friel|first2=Coleen|last3=Raddick|first3=Robert|publisher=NYU Press|year=2001|isbn=0814742475|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe government offered Gambino a [[plea bargain]] that included a guilty admission, a $12 million [[restitution]] payment, and a promise to leave the garment trucking business. In February 1992, Gambino accepted the plea bargain and avoided prison.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/06/16/magazine/the-attorney-general-goes-to-war.html?scp=18&sq=&pagewanted=3 \"The Attorney General Goes To War\"] New York Times Magazine June 16, 2002</ref> Prosecutors would remark that a \"terrifying fear of prison\" helped motivate Gambino to accept the government deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/27/nyregion/gambinos-to-quit-trucking-business-in-a-plea-bargain.html?scp=28&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|title=GAMBINOS TO QUIT TRUCKING BUSINESS IN A PLEA BARGAIN|last=Blumenthal|first=Ralph|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 27, 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304132318/https://www.nytimes.com/1992/02/27/nyregion/gambinos-to-quit-trucking-business-in-a-plea-bargain.html?scp=28&sq=%22Thomas+Gambino%22&st=nyt|archive-date=March 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Indictment and prison==\nIn 1991, Gambino, Gotti, [[Sammy Gravano|Salvatore \"Sammy the Bull\" Gravano]] and other Gambino mobsters were indicted on charges of racketeering, loansharking, extortion, illegal gambling and 11 counts of murder.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/12/12/nyregion/gotti-and-3-top-aides-arrested-on-federal-racketeering-charges.html?scp=23&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=Gotti and 3 Top Aides Arrested On Federal Racketeering Charges|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 12, 1990}}</ref> Soon after the indictment, Gravano decided to become a government witness and testified against his former colleagues, including Gambino.\n\nOn May 11, 1993, Gambino was convicted of two counts of racketeering and racketeering conspiracy. Prosecutors claimed that Gambino had been supervising illegal gambling and [[loansharking]] activities in [[Connecticut]] since 1985.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/05/12/nyregion/thomas-gambino-is-guilty-of-racketeering.html?scp=2&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=Thomas Gambino Is Guilty of Racketeering|last=|first=|date=May 12, 1993|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=December 9, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> In January 1996, Gambino started serving a five-year prison sentence.<ref name=\"nytimes.com\"/>\n\nIn May 1999, the U.S. [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) filed fraud charges against Gambino's stockbroker, Mohammed Ali Khan. While still in prison, Gambino had sued Khan for defrauding him out of approximately $2 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/18/nyregion/metro-news-briefs-new-york-sec-sues-broker-accused-of-theft.html?scp=22&sq=%22Thomas%20Gambino%22&st=cse|title=METRO NEWS BRIEFS: NEW YORK; S.E.C. Sues Broker Accused of Theft|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 18, 1999}}</ref>\n\nOn May 10, 2000, Gambino was released from prison.<ref>[http://www.bop.gov/iloc2/InmateFinderServlet?Transaction=NameSearch&needingMoreList=false&FirstName=Thomas&Middle=&LastName=Gambino&Race=U&Sex=U&Age=&x=28&y=20 Bureau of Prisons Inmate Locator]</ref> He has moved to Florida and is now believed to be retired.\n\n==Popular culture==\nThomas Gambino is portrayed by [[Tony Sirico]] in the 1998 made-for-television movie ''[[Witness to the Mob]]'' about Gravano and John Gotti.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Bonanno|first=Joseph|title=A Man of Honor: The Autobiography of Joseph Bonanno|location=New York|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2003|isbn=0-312-97923-1|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Capeci|first1=Jerry|last2=Mustain|first2=Gene|title=Gotti: Rise and Fall|location=New York|publisher=Onyx|year=1996|isbn=0-451-40681-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/gottirisefall00cape}}\n*{{cite book|last=Capeci|first=Jerry|title=The Complete Idiot's Guide to the Mafia|location=Indianapolis|publisher=Alpha Books|date=2002|isbn=0-02-864225-2|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/completeidiotsgu0000cape}}\n*{{cite book|last=Davis|first=John H.|title=Mafia Dynasty: The Rise and Fall of the Gambino Crime Family|location=New York|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1993|isbn=0-06-109184-7|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/mafiadynastyrise00davi}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Jacobs|first1=James B.|last2=Panarella|first2=Christopher|last3=Worthington|first3=Jay|title=Busting the Mob: The United States Vs. Cosa Nostra|location=New York|publisher=NYU Press|year=1994|isbn=0-8147-4230-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Maas|first=Peter|title=Underboss: Sammy the Bull Gravano's Story of Life in the Mafia|location=New York|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|year=1997|isbn=0-06-093096-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Raab|first=Selwyn|title=Five Families: The Rise, Decline, and Resurgence of America's Most Powerful Mafia Empires|location=New York|publisher=St. Martin Press|year=2005|isbn=0-312-30094-8}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite news|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126051608/http://www.thelaborers.net/lexisnexis/articles/verdict_is_termed_a_blow_to_the.htm|last=Blumenthal|first=Ralph|date=November 20, 1986|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=January 24, 2007|url-status=live|title=Verdict Is Termed a Blow to The Mafia}}\n*[http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_hb4298/is_198911/ai_n14997496 Thomas Gambino] on FindArticels\n\n{{Gambino crime family}}{{American Mafia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gambino, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American mobsters of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Gambino crime family]]\n[[Category:Manhattan College alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Lido Beach, New York]]\n[[Category:People from the Upper East Side]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Gambino"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin\n|image             = T.C.Chamberlin.gif\n|image_size       =\n|caption           = Chamberlin in the 1870s\n|birth_date        = September 25, 1843\n|birth_place       = [[Mattoon, Illinois]]\n|death_date        = {{d-da|November 15, 1928|September 25, 1843}}\n|death_place       = [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]\n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = American\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Geology]]\n|work_institutions = [[Columbian University]]<br>[[University of Wisconsin]]<br>[[University of Chicago]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Beloit College]] {{small|(A.B., 1866)}}<br>[[University of Michigan]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Alexander Winchell]]\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = [[Planetesimal Hypothesis]]\n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = [[Hayden Memorial Geological Award]] {{small|(1920)}}<br>[[Penrose Gold Medal]] <small>(1924)</small><br />[[Penrose Medal]] <small>(1927)</small>\n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n|children = [[Rollin Thomas Chamberlin]] (1881\u20131948), geologist and skeptic of [[Alfred Wegener|Wegener]]'s [[continental drift]] hypothesis\n}}\n'''Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|r|a\u028a|d|\u0259r|}};<ref>''Webster's New Biographical Dictionary'' (Springfield, Mass.: Merriam-Webster, 1988; {{ISBN|9780877795438}}), p. 1099.</ref> September 25, 1843 \u2013 November 15, 1928) was an American [[geologist]] and [[educator]]. In 1893 he founded the ''[[Journal of Geology]]'', of which he was editor for many years.\n\n==Biography==\nChamberlin was born September 25, 1843, in [[Mattoon, Illinois]]. When he was three years old his family moved north to near [[Beloit, Wisconsin]]. His father was a [[Methodist]] circuit minister and farmer. He attended a preparatory academy before entering [[Beloit College]], where he received a classical education in Greek and Latin, while becoming interested in natural science. While a student at Beloit he directed a church choir and participated in athletics and debate.\n\nAfter graduation from [[Beloit College]] in 1866, Chamberlin worked for two years as a teacher and later principal in a high school near Beloit. He was married to Alma Wilson in 1867.\n\nIn 1868\u20131869, Chamberlin spent a year taking graduate courses, including geology, at the [[University of Michigan]] to strengthen his scientific background. Subsequently (1869\u20131873), he became professor of natural science at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Whitewater|Whitewater Normal School]] in Wisconsin. He joined the Beloit faculty in 1873, where he was professor of geology, [[zoology]], and [[botany]]. In 1873 he also became one of several part-time participants in conducting a comprehensive geological survey of [[Wisconsin]]. His [[geologic map]]ping work in southeastern Wisconsin, a region mantled with thick [[glacial deposit]]s, led him to recognize multiple episodes of [[glaciation]] during the [[Pleistocene]]. His terminology for [[glacial stage]]s in North America is still in use, with minor modifications.\n\nIn 1875 he started a business with his brother and sold spring water, a popular brand at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beloit.edu/archives/documents/archival_documents/chamberlin_springs/|title=Chamberlin Springs: Rest & Research Since 1875|publisher=Beloit College}}</ref>\n\nIn 1876 Chamberlin became chief geologist for the Wisconsin geological survey, supervising the completion of the survey and the publication of the four-volume report, for which he authored sections on glacial deposits, [[Paleozoic]] and [[Precambrian]] [[bedrock]] geology, [[Carbonate hosted lead zinc ore deposits|lead-zinc ore deposits]], [[artesian well]]s, and [[soil]]s. The project brought him national attention and led to his appointment as head of the glacial division of the [[US Geological Survey]] in 1881. He later was president of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] (1887 to 1892).\n\nIn 1890<ref>{{cite journal|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1890|title=The method of multiple working hypotheses|journal=Science |volume=15 |pages=92\u201396}}</ref>, and again in 1897<ref>{{cite journal|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1897|title=Studies for students: the method of multiple working hypotheses|journal=Journal of Geology |volume=5 |issue=8|pages=837\u2013848|jstor=30054868|doi=10.1086/607980}}</ref>, Chamberlin wrote ''The method of multiple working hypotheses'', in which he advocated the importance of simultaneously evaluating several hypotheses, rejecting those that conflict with available data, and ending with the one hypothesis supported by the data. This stood in contrast to what he called the ''single ruling theory'', which encouraged scientists to find supporting data and not challenge it with difficult tests. The paper is considered a landmark <ref>{{cite journal|last = Elliot|first = L.P.|author2=B. W. Brook |title = Revisiting Chamberlin: multiple working hypotheses for the 21st century|journal = BioScience|date=2007|volume=57|issue = 7|pages=608&ndash;614|doi=10.1641/B570708}}</ref> on the scientific method, was an inspiration for the approach called [[strong inference]], and was reprinted in 1965.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1965|title=The method of multiple working hypotheses|journal=Science |volume=148 |issue=3671|pages=754\u2013759|doi=10.1126/science.148.3671.754|pmid=17748786|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3d22814c199f0f956734d59dfd066d43e64f3a8d}}</ref>\n\nIn 1892 Chamberlin accepted the offer to organize a department of geology at the new [[University of Chicago]], where he remained as a professor until 1918.  From 1898 to 1914 he was president of the [[Chicago Academy of Sciences]].\n\nIn 1899 Chamberlin wrote, ''An Attempt to Frame a Working Hypothesis of the Cause of Glacial Periods on an Atmospheric Basis'', and developed at length the idea that changes in climate could result from changes in the concentration of atmospheric carbon dioxide, and wrote about [[climate engineering|climate actions]]:\n{{quote|When the temperature is rising after a glacial episode, dissociation is promoted, and the ocean gives forth its carbon dioxide at an increased rate, and thereby assists in accelerating the amelioration of climate.\n\nA study of the life of the geological periods seems to indicate that there were very notable fluctuations in the total mass of living matter. To be sure there was a reciprocal relation between the life of the land and that of the sea, so that when the latter was extended upon the continental platforms and greatly augmented, the former was contracted, but notwithstanding this it seems clear that the sum of life activity fluctuated notably during the ages. It is believed that on the whole it was greatest at the periods of sea extension and mild climates, and least at the times of disruption and climatic intensification. This factor then acted antithetically to the carbonic acid freeing previously noted, and, so far as it went, tended to offset its effects\n\nIt now becomes necessary to assign agencies capable of removing carbon dioxide from the atmosphere at a rate sufficiently above the normal rate of supply, at certain times, to produce glaciation; and on the other hand, capable of restoring it to the atmosphere at certain other times in sufficient amounts to produce mild climates.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/details/jstor-30055497|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1899|title=An Attempt to Frame a Working Hypothesis of the Cause of Glacial Periods on an Atmospheric Basis|journal=Journal of Geology |volume=7 |issue=8|pages=751\u2013787|doi=10.1086/608524|bibcode=1899JG......7..751C}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1905, Chamberlin and [[Forest Ray Moulton]] developed a theory of the formation of the [[solar system]] that challenged the [[Pierre-Simon Laplace|Laplacian]] [[nebular hypothesis]].  Their theory, the [[Chamberlin-Moulton planetesimal hypothesis]], received favorable support for almost a third of a century, but passed out of favor by the late 1930s.  It ultimately was discarded in the 1940s by the realization it was incompatible with the [[angular momentum]] of [[Jupiter]]. A portion of the theory stating that smaller objects &mdash; [[planetesimal]]s &mdash; gradually collided to build the planets by [[accretion theory|accretion]] is still well-regarded. From his theories and other geological evidence he concluded that Earth was much older than assumed by [[Lord Kelvin]] (ca 100 million years) at the time. His speculations about the source of energy for such a long-lived Sun were prescient, involving the ability of the Sun to somehow extract energy from the inner structures of the atom.\n\nChamberlin was awarded the inaugural [[Penrose Gold Medal]] of the [[Society of Economic Geologists]] in 1924,<ref name=seg>{{cite web |url=http://www.segweb.org/SEG/_About_SEG/_Medals_and_Awards/Penrose_Gold_Medal.aspx |title=Penrose Gold Medal |publisher=Society of Economic Geologists |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121228070411/http://www.segweb.org/SEG/_About_SEG/_Medals_and_Awards/Penrose_Gold_Medal.aspx |archivedate=28 December 2012 }}</ref> and the inaugural [[Penrose Medal]] of the [[Geological Society of America]] in 1927.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geosociety.org/awards/past.htm#penrose |title=Penrose Medalists |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |publisher=The Geological Society of America, Inc.}}</ref> He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1894.<ref>Eckel, Edwin, 1982, GSA Memoir 155, The Geological Society of America \u2014 Life History of a Learned Society, {{ISBN|0-8137-1155-X}}.</ref>\n\nChamberlin remained active professionally up until his death in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] on November 15, 1928.\n\nHis papers are housed at the University of Chicago archives and the Beloit College archives. The Beloit College archives also contain the papers of his son, [[Rollin T. Chamberlin]], who was also a geologist.<ref>Beloit College Archives, {{cite web|url=http://www.beloit.edu/~archives/documents/archival_collections/alumni/thomas_chamberlin.php|title=Thomas C. Chamberlin}}</ref> There are buildings named for him on the Beloit College and University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison campuses as well as a house in [[Burton-Judson Courts]] at [[The University of Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://housing.sites.uchicago.edu/Chamberlin-house|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103232209/http://housing.sites.uchicago.edu/Chamberlin-house|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 3, 2014|title=Chamberlin House|accessdate=January 3, 2014}}</ref> The [[Chamberlin (lunar crater)|lunar crater Chamberlin]] and a [[Impact crater|crater]] on [[Mars]]<ref name=deVaucouleurs1975>{{cite journal | title=The new Martian nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union | display-authors=1 | last1=de Vaucouleurs | first1=G. | last2=Blunck | first2=J. | last3=Davies | first3=M. | last4=Dollfus | first4=A. | last5=Koval | first5=I. K. | last6=Kuiper | first6=G. P. | last7=Masursky | first7=H. | last8=Miyamoto | first8=S. | last9=Moroz | first9=V. I. | last10=Sagan | first10=Carl | last11=Smith | first11=Bradford | journal=Icarus | volume=26 | issue=1 | date=September 1975 | pages=85\u221298 | doi=10.1016/0019-1035(75)90146-3 | bibcode=1975Icar...26...85D }}</ref> are named in his honor.\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of climate change science]]\n*[[wikibooks:Geological Features of Wisconsin|''Geological Features of Wisconsin'']]\n*[[Ice Age Trail]]\n*[[Strong inference]]\n\n==Works==\n* ''Outline of a Course of Oral Instruction'' (1872)\n* ''Geology of Wisconsin'' (1877)\n* Preliminary paper on the terminal moraine of the second glacial epoch (U.S. Geological Survey, 1882) \n* [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001520289 The rock scorings of the great ice invasions] (U.S. Geological Survey, 1886)\n* {{cite journal |year=1890 |title=The Method of Multiple Working Hypotheses |url=http://arti.vub.ac.be/cursus/2005-2006/mwo/chamberlin1890science.pdf |journal=Science |volume=15 |issue=366 |pages=92\u201396 | doi=10.1126/science.ns-15.366.92|pmid=17782687 |bibcode=1890Sci....15R..92. }}\n* [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001488672 ''Contribution to the Theory of Glacial Motion''] (1904)\n* With [[Rollin D. Salisbury|R. D. Salisbury]], ''Geology'' (three volumes, 1907\u201309)\n* ''The Origin of the Earth'' (1916)\n* \"[http://www.nasonline.org/publications/biographical-memoirs/memoir-pdfs/chamberlin-thomas-c.pdf Biographical Memoir of Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin: 1843-1928]\". In ''Biographical Memoirs, vol. 15''. Washington: National Academy of Sciences.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | author = Dott Robert H. Jr | year = 2006 | title = Rock Stars: Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin (1843\u20131928) | journal = GSA Today | volume = 16 | issue = 10| pages = 30\u201331 | doi = 10.1130/1052-5173(2006)16[30:RSTCC]2.0.CO;2 }}\n* Railsback,  L. Bruce. \"[http://www.gly.uga.edu/railsback/11111misc/MWHReprise2.pdf T. C. Chamberlin's 'Method of Multiple Working Hypotheses': An encapsulation for modern students]\".\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*{{Internet Archive author|sname=Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin}}\n*[https://www.beloit.edu/archives/assets/Chamberlin_Finding_Aid_MC_31.pdf Chamberlin holdings at Beloit College Archives]\n*[http://dcms.beloit.edu/cdm4/browse.php?CISOROOT=%2Fchamber Expedition photographs from Beloit College Digital Collections]\n*[http://academic.emporia.edu/aberjame/histgeol/chamber/chamber.htm Biography by James S. Aber]\n* {{Librivox author |id=11437}}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n* [https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/e/scrc/findingaids/view.php?eadid=ICU.SPCL.CHAMBERLINTC Guide to the Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin Papers 1878-1932] at the [https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/scrc/ University of Chicago Special Collections Research Center]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of Presidents and Chancellors of the University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|President]] of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] | before= [[John Bascom]] | after = [[Charles Kendall Adams|Charles K. Adams]] | years=1887-1892}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of the Geological Society of America}}\n{{University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison leaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chamberlin, Thomas Chrowder}}\n[[Category:1843 births]]\n[[Category:1928 deaths]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the University of Wisconsin-Madison]]\n[[Category:American geologists]]\n[[Category:American science writers]]\n[[Category:Beloit College alumni]]\n[[Category:Beloit College faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin&ndash;Whitewater faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Mattoon, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Science teachers]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Michigan alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Beloit, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Penrose Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Writers from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Geological Society of America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name              = Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin\n|image             = T.C.Chamberlin.gif\n|image_size       =\n|caption           = Chamberlin in the 1870s\n|birth_date        = September 25, 1843\n|birth_place       = [[Mattoon, Illinois]]\n|death_date        = {{d-da|November 15, 1928|September 25, 1843}}\n|death_place       = [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]\n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = American\n|ethnicity         = \n|field             = [[Geology]]\n|work_institutions = [[Columbian University]]<br>[[University of Wisconsin]]<br>[[University of Chicago]]\n|alma_mater        = [[Beloit College]] {{small|(A.B., 1866)}}<br>[[University of Michigan]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = [[Alexander Winchell]]\n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = [[Planetesimal Hypothesis]]\n|author_abbrev_bot = \n|author_abbrev_zoo = \n|influences        = \n|influenced        = \n|prizes            = [[Hayden Memorial Geological Award]] {{small|(1920)}}<br>[[Penrose Gold Medal]] <small>(1924)</small><br />[[Penrose Medal]] <small>(1927)</small>\n|religion          = \n|footnotes         = \n|signature         =\n|children = [[Rollin Thomas Chamberlin]] (1881\u20131948), geologist and skeptic of [[Alfred Wegener|Wegener]]'s [[continental drift]] hypothesis\n}}\n'''Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|r|a\u028a|d|\u0259r|}};<ref>''Webster's New Biographical Dictionary'' (Springfield, Mass.: Merriam-Webster, 1988; {{ISBN|9780877795438}}), p. 1099.</ref> September 25, 1843 \u2013 November 15, 1928) was an American [[geologist]] and [[educator]]. In 1893 he founded the ''[[Journal of Geology]]'', of which he was editor for many years.\n\n==Biography==\nChamberlin was born September 25, 1843, in [[Mattoon, Illinois]]. When he was three years old his family moved north to near [[Beloit, Wisconsin]]. His father was a [[Methodist]] circuit minister and farmer. He attended a preparatory academy before entering [[Beloit College]], where he received a classical education in Greek and Latin, while becoming interested in natural science. While a student at Beloit he directed a church choir and participated in athletics and debate.\n\nAfter graduation from [[Beloit College]] in 1866, Chamberlin worked for two years as a teacher and later principal in a high school near Beloit. He was married to Alma Wilson in 1867.\n\nIn 1868\u20131869, Chamberlin spent a year taking graduate courses, including geology, at the [[University of Michigan]] to strengthen his scientific background. Subsequently (1869\u20131873), he became professor of natural science at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Whitewater|Whitewater Normal School]] in Wisconsin. He joined the Beloit faculty in 1873, where he was professor of geology, [[zoology]], and [[botany]]. In 1873 he also became one of several part-time participants in conducting a comprehensive geological survey of [[Wisconsin]]. His [[geologic map]]ping work in southeastern Wisconsin, a region mantled with thick [[glacial deposit]]s, led him to recognize multiple episodes of [[glaciation]] during the [[Pleistocene]]. His terminology for [[glacial stage]]s in North America is still in use, with minor modifications.\n\nIn 1875 he started a business with his brother and sold spring water, a popular brand at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beloit.edu/archives/documents/archival_documents/chamberlin_springs/|title=Chamberlin Springs: Rest & Research Since 1875|publisher=Beloit College}}</ref>\n\nIn 1876 Chamberlin became chief geologist for the Wisconsin geological survey, supervising the completion of the survey and the publication of the four-volume report, for which he authored sections on glacial deposits, [[Paleozoic]] and [[Precambrian]] [[bedrock]] geology, [[Carbonate hosted lead zinc ore deposits|lead-zinc ore deposits]], [[artesian well]]s, and [[soil]]s. The project brought him national attention and led to his appointment as head of the glacial division of the [[US Geological Survey]] in 1881. He later was president of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] (1887 to 1892).\n\nIn 1890<ref>{{cite journal|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1890|title=The method of multiple working hypotheses|journal=Science |volume=15 |pages=92\u201396}}</ref>, and again in 1897<ref>{{cite journal|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1897|title=Studies for students: the method of multiple working hypotheses|journal=Journal of Geology |volume=5 |issue=8|pages=837\u2013848|jstor=30054868|doi=10.1086/607980}}</ref>, Chamberlin wrote ''The method of multiple working hypotheses'', in which he advocated the importance of simultaneously evaluating several hypotheses, rejecting those that conflict with available data, and ending with the one hypothesis supported by the data. This stood in contrast to what he called the ''single ruling theory'', which encouraged scientists to find supporting data and not challenge it with difficult tests. The paper is considered a landmark <ref>{{cite journal|last = Elliot|first = L.P.|author2=B. W. Brook |title = Revisiting Chamberlin: multiple working hypotheses for the 21st century|journal = BioScience|date=2007|volume=57|issue = 7|pages=608&ndash;614|doi=10.1641/B570708}}</ref> on the scientific method, was an inspiration for the approach called [[strong inference]], and was reprinted in 1965<ref>{{cite journal|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1965|title=The method of multiple working hypotheses|journal=Science |volume=148 |issue=3671|pages=754\u2013759|doi=10.1126/science.148.3671.754|pmid=17748786|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3d22814c199f0f956734d59dfd066d43e64f3a8d}}</ref>.\n\nIn 1892 Chamberlin accepted the offer to organize a department of geology at the new [[University of Chicago]], where he remained as a professor until 1918.  From 1898 to 1914 he was president of the [[Chicago Academy of Sciences]].\n\nIn 1899 Chamberlin wrote, ''An Attempt to Frame a Working Hypothesis of the Cause of Glacial Periods on an Atmospheric Basis'', and developed at length the idea that changes in climate could result from changes in the concentration of atmospheric carbon dioxide, and wrote about [[climate engineering|climate actions]]:\n{{quote|When the temperature is rising after a glacial episode, dissociation is promoted, and the ocean gives forth its carbon dioxide at an increased rate, and thereby assists in accelerating the amelioration of climate.\n\nA study of the life of the geological periods seems to indicate that there were very notable fluctuations in the total mass of living matter. To be sure there was a reciprocal relation between the life of the land and that of the sea, so that when the latter was extended upon the continental platforms and greatly augmented, the former was contracted, but notwithstanding this it seems clear that the sum of life activity fluctuated notably during the ages. It is believed that on the whole it was greatest at the periods of sea extension and mild climates, and least at the times of disruption and climatic intensification. This factor then acted antithetically to the carbonic acid freeing previously noted, and, so far as it went, tended to offset its effects\n\nIt now becomes necessary to assign agencies capable of removing carbon dioxide from the atmosphere at a rate sufficiently above the normal rate of supply, at certain times, to produce glaciation; and on the other hand, capable of restoring it to the atmosphere at certain other times in sufficient amounts to produce mild climates.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/details/jstor-30055497|author=Chamberlin, T. C.|year=1899|title=An Attempt to Frame a Working Hypothesis of the Cause of Glacial Periods on an Atmospheric Basis|journal=Journal of Geology |volume=7 |issue=8|pages=751\u2013787|doi=10.1086/608524|bibcode=1899JG......7..751C}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1905, Chamberlin and [[Forest Ray Moulton]] developed a theory of the formation of the [[solar system]] that challenged the [[Pierre-Simon Laplace|Laplacian]] [[nebular hypothesis]].  Their theory, the [[Chamberlin-Moulton planetesimal hypothesis]], received favorable support for almost a third of a century, but passed out of favor by the late 1930s.  It ultimately was discarded in the 1940s by the realization it was incompatible with the [[angular momentum]] of [[Jupiter]]. A portion of the theory stating that smaller objects &mdash; [[planetesimal]]s &mdash; gradually collided to build the planets by [[accretion theory|accretion]] is still well-regarded. From his theories and other geological evidence he concluded that Earth was much older than assumed by [[Lord Kelvin]] (ca 100 million years) at the time. His speculations about the source of energy for such a long-lived Sun were prescient, involving the ability of the Sun to somehow extract energy from the inner structures of the atom.\n\nChamberlin was awarded the inaugural [[Penrose Gold Medal]] of the [[Society of Economic Geologists]] in 1924,<ref name=seg>{{cite web |url=http://www.segweb.org/SEG/_About_SEG/_Medals_and_Awards/Penrose_Gold_Medal.aspx |title=Penrose Gold Medal |publisher=Society of Economic Geologists |accessdate=15 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121228070411/http://www.segweb.org/SEG/_About_SEG/_Medals_and_Awards/Penrose_Gold_Medal.aspx |archivedate=28 December 2012 }}</ref> and the inaugural [[Penrose Medal]] of the [[Geological Society of America]] in 1927.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geosociety.org/awards/past.htm#penrose |title=Penrose Medalists |accessdate=May 15, 2012 |publisher=The Geological Society of America, Inc.}}</ref> He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1894.<ref>Eckel, Edwin, 1982, GSA Memoir 155, The Geological Society of America \u2014 Life History of a Learned Society, {{ISBN|0-8137-1155-X}}.</ref>\n\nChamberlin remained active professionally up until his death in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] on November 15, 1928.\n\nHis papers are housed at the University of Chicago archives and the Beloit College archives. The Beloit College archives also contain the papers of his son, [[Rollin T. Chamberlin]], who was also a geologist.<ref>Beloit College Archives, {{cite web|url=http://www.beloit.edu/~archives/documents/archival_collections/alumni/thomas_chamberlin.php|title=Thomas C. Chamberlin}}</ref> There are buildings named for him on the Beloit College and University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison campuses as well as a house in [[Burton-Judson Courts]] at [[The University of Chicago]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://housing.sites.uchicago.edu/Chamberlin-house|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103232209/http://housing.sites.uchicago.edu/Chamberlin-house|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 3, 2014|title=Chamberlin House|accessdate=January 3, 2014}}</ref> The [[Chamberlin (lunar crater)|lunar crater Chamberlin]] and a [[Impact crater|crater]] on [[Mars]]<ref name=deVaucouleurs1975>{{cite journal | title=The new Martian nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union | display-authors=1 | last1=de Vaucouleurs | first1=G. | last2=Blunck | first2=J. | last3=Davies | first3=M. | last4=Dollfus | first4=A. | last5=Koval | first5=I. K. | last6=Kuiper | first6=G. P. | last7=Masursky | first7=H. | last8=Miyamoto | first8=S. | last9=Moroz | first9=V. I. | last10=Sagan | first10=Carl | last11=Smith | first11=Bradford | journal=Icarus | volume=26 | issue=1 | date=September 1975 | pages=85\u221298 | doi=10.1016/0019-1035(75)90146-3 | bibcode=1975Icar...26...85D }}</ref> are named in his honor.\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of climate change science]]\n*[[wikibooks:Geological Features of Wisconsin|''Geological Features of Wisconsin'']]\n*[[Ice Age Trail]]\n*[[Strong inference]]\n\n==Works==\n* ''Outline of a Course of Oral Instruction'' (1872)\n* ''Geology of Wisconsin'' (1877)\n* Preliminary paper on the terminal moraine of the second glacial epoch (U.S. Geological Survey, 1882) \n* [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001520289 The rock scorings of the great ice invasions] (U.S. Geological Survey, 1886)\n* {{cite journal |year=1890 |title=The Method of Multiple Working Hypotheses |url=http://arti.vub.ac.be/cursus/2005-2006/mwo/chamberlin1890science.pdf |journal=Science |volume=15 |issue=366 |pages=92\u201396 | doi=10.1126/science.ns-15.366.92|pmid=17782687 |bibcode=1890Sci....15R..92. }}\n* [http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/001488672 ''Contribution to the Theory of Glacial Motion''] (1904)\n* With [[Rollin D. Salisbury|R. D. Salisbury]], ''Geology'' (three volumes, 1907\u201309)\n* ''The Origin of the Earth'' (1916)\n* \"[http://www.nasonline.org/publications/biographical-memoirs/memoir-pdfs/chamberlin-thomas-c.pdf Biographical Memoir of Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin: 1843-1928]\". In ''Biographical Memoirs, vol. 15''. Washington: National Academy of Sciences.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | author = Dott Robert H. Jr | year = 2006 | title = Rock Stars: Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin (1843\u20131928) | journal = GSA Today | volume = 16 | issue = 10| pages = 30\u201331 | doi = 10.1130/1052-5173(2006)16[30:RSTCC]2.0.CO;2 }}\n* Railsback,  L. Bruce. \"[http://www.gly.uga.edu/railsback/11111misc/MWHReprise2.pdf T. C. Chamberlin's 'Method of Multiple Working Hypotheses': An encapsulation for modern students]\".\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*{{Internet Archive author|sname=Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin}}\n*[https://www.beloit.edu/archives/assets/Chamberlin_Finding_Aid_MC_31.pdf Chamberlin holdings at Beloit College Archives]\n*[http://dcms.beloit.edu/cdm4/browse.php?CISOROOT=%2Fchamber Expedition photographs from Beloit College Digital Collections]\n*[http://academic.emporia.edu/aberjame/histgeol/chamber/chamber.htm Biography by James S. Aber]\n* {{Librivox author |id=11437}}\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n* [https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/e/scrc/findingaids/view.php?eadid=ICU.SPCL.CHAMBERLINTC Guide to the Thomas Chrowder Chamberlin Papers 1878-1932] at the [https://www.lib.uchicago.edu/scrc/ University of Chicago Special Collections Research Center]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box | title=[[List of Presidents and Chancellors of the University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|President]] of the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] | before= [[John Bascom]] | after = [[Charles Kendall Adams|Charles K. Adams]] | years=1887-1892}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of the Geological Soc